#X text 503 31 Below we have the [bp~] bandpass filter \, a native object that only accepts control messages for its central frequency. In this case you can't use a signal LFO \, unless you convert from signal to floats \, using something like [sig2float~]. The [rescale] object from ELSE is also useful for remapping control data., f 50;
#X text 256 138 The [rescale~] object from ELSE is convenient for rescaling audio signals into a new control range (here it maps the -1 to 1 input range to an output range from 500 to 1500)., f 26;
#X obj 533 187 setdsp~;
#X obj 301 26 declare -path else;
#X text 25 68 "LFOs" (Low Frequency Oscillators) are just any oscillator running at a low frequency \, simple as that! We use them to control all sorts of parameters in a patch. Below we have a sine wave controlling the frequency of a filter.;
#X text 513 377 Both [rescale] and [rescale~] can also map with exponential curves and may take any input range as well. Check their help files for more details., f 49;
#X obj 318 468 phasor~ 1;
#X obj 319 498 phasor 1;
#X text 35 465 [phasor~] with a low frequency can also be thouhgt of as a "LFO'. And not that ELSE has a control [phasor] object., f 36;
#X obj 209 676 out~;
#X obj 149 639 pimp~ 0.5;
#X text 34 538 [pimp~] from ELSE combines [phasor~] and [imp~] (a trigger). The impulse is given at period transitions. This is useful at low frequencies and we'll see applications for it in this tutorial. Check its help file.;
